"everyone deserves respect. we deserve respect." #respetonaman is a nationwide campaign against gender-based violence. the goal of the project is to spark a sustainable movement across the nation to eliminate all forms of gender-based violence in the philippines through campaigning for awareness, empowerment, and policy.

as inspired by the global #metoo, and #timesup movement and thailandâ€™s #donttellmehowtodress movement, it will focus on bringing the issue into the mainstream and empowering women to rise up against all forms of gender-based violence.

in line with this year's 16-days of activism against gender-based violence, #respetonaman will hold a series of events and programs which would include two big forums, an online campaign, and a localized version of the #donttellmehowtodress exhibit.

#respetonaman is a project of the office of  vp leni robredo, un women safe cities metro manila programme, the embassy of sweden in manila, spark philippines, and #empower; supported by don'ttellmehowtodress thailand, cindy sirinya bishop, bdo unibank, sanggunian ng mga paaralang loyola ng ateneo de manila, osci (office of social  concern and involvement of ateneo de manila university), and power plant mall.

follow our campaign page to join the movement: facebook.com/respetonamanph

text:
hello to my followers, friends and family : )

my creative block is more than i imaginedâ€¦â€¦ i have taken a leave of absence from social media to focus on the most difficult personal healing process, i could have imagined.

diagnosed with complex ptsd only a year ago, i am now experiencing an intensity of subconscious resistance to the psychological therapy or onion peeling process.  no easy feat tearing down a well armoured, inner child and psyche.  built to defend me against early childhood mental, emotional and sexual abusers, and the over whelming life long trauma around my #metoo struggles. 
a second chakra blockage of epic proportions, i reel, as i am reluctant to let go of my defences â€¦.. my roar ! , as my badger spirit, did a great job of protecting me.  at times i had to fight hard, at times i fled â€¦. more often i fought my way out of things.  even a black bear attack, badger came to my rescue.

take good care, as you journey in life.  take those early childhood attacks on your wee psyche seriously, as i am finding out it is insidious, and now proven to get worse in adult onset. with many known diseases and disorders coming to fruition later in life, as well as , cognitive impairment from the stress of abuse. #protectthechildrenfromsexualabuse 
my therapist has begun emdr work : eye movement desensitization and reprocessing.  what a ride.

eight sessions. four to break me open and poke around the bad memories . stirring me up to trigger memories / responses,  then four more to install more positive memories of myself .

informing me, it gets worse before it gets better : / â€¦â€¦ i journey on.

i suspect, my art will be evolving along with me.

stay tuned.

big wild wounded woman hugs to us all xo

#complexptsd #survivingchildabuse #metoo #metoomovement #bullies #shunning #reconstructingmypsyche #woundedwarriors #creativeblock #compassion #posttraumaticstressdisorder #peaceandlovetothechildren #survivor #healing

text: this hits me in so many areas of my life. first obviously, being i am an almost 26 year old trying to pursue ballet and it's not a cake walk. but my work from home, my past of abuse, my marriage that's surviving on strings of therapy and group recovery, and the lack of being able to conceive children without some kind of miracle. all these things that people don't see but want to be strong like us, i have to laugh. (sarcastically) cause i personally wouldn't go through this if i had a choice and i am hoping to keep my son from the same fate. but ballet and creating my own business takes all my anger and hurt and pain and puts it towards me. i get to choose to work hard for something for myself. #avoiceandachoice #ballet #successquotes #life #hercrowningglory #killingit #inforthelongrun #metoo #hardwork

text:
"panty portrait: cooch" from the panty project, 9 of 51
.

fiber art, archival pigment print on museum cotton rag, 
19 x 14 inches
.
the panty project is an ongoing social practice project. participants, womxn and those who identify as womxn, courageously share with me their stories of experienced gendered transgressions and violent aggressions, whether cultural and/or interpersonal. participants write a word or phrase onto the panel of their selected undergarment; i hand-embroider over their mark-making and photograph them as if they have been taken off. this work addresses the inherent misogyny within our language, and the consequential "essestializing" of womxn, which reduces womxn, and those who identify as womxn, to "less than." this work is about healing and transcendence. 
womxn's long-silenced voices must be heard.
.

text:
so i needed some time to process and react, if necessary. on a night in march 2009, i experienced another sexual assault, while out with someone who was my friend. when i woke up to pain and bruising on various parts of my body, i was in shock. but quickly realised what happened. i questioned why god let this happen to me again. why did i have to endure another one?! what the fuck kind of karma do i have and why canâ€™t i get rid of it? turning inward, i stopped having fun, dating, exercising...living life. drinking and comfort food consoled me, but i always felt empty. 
i saw him this weekend. and instead of experiencing a flashback, anxiety, crying or retreating i ignored him. he  grabbed my hand to say hello, because i refused to acknowledge him. i responded with indifference. 
and was not triggered by his presence or energy. my friends were upset by his being in close proximity and i was fine. iâ€™m still fine. 
in my growth, i understand why he felt it necessary to take what was not his. there was power and control gained by what he did. when i said no to his previous advances, that was his trigger. the assault was the result. 
it has taken a great amount of love for myself to arrive at this level of understanding, forgiveness, and resilience. and for this i am beyond grateful and beaming with pride. (2/2)  #shethrives #forgiveyourself #stillstanding #diamondstrong #badass #survivor #metoo #writeon #resilience #writeaboutit #writingistherapy #writersofinstagram #jemilada

when you watch what's going on in the white house these days, it's hard to remember that things were ever different. ever more possible, ever more hopeful. every more anything-other-than-what-weâ€™re-seeing-now... so i've been bumping this joint the last couple days just for the memories.  i actually knew a couple people that worked in this projectâ€”it's long story for another time from my "old life". maybe i'll tell it one day. 
anyway, this was probably the first "official" mixtape in political history for a mjor  candidate.
the man himself big rush had his name on this one. he's vanished under a cloud of #metoo rape accusations in recent years... but before that, russell simmons was as public an entrepreneur and ipresario as hiphop had. and even in 2008, he was an og whose approval still mattered.
so him and em's fave dj green lantern leaked this everywhere--datpiff, tss... every major blog had it at one point.

i'll talk more about this later. but google around. it's still up in a couple places.

it's worth running back!

text:
my 2019 diary. a treat to myself for being accepted into a bachelor of health science (midwifery). my powerful sisters who have come before me and who will follow me mean that this is possible. a modern feminist is so much more. we don't just fight for ourselves, but for others, trans, gay, people of colour, indigenous rights. human rights are human rights. they don't come with colour, gender or a biological sex. "it took me quite a long time to develop a voice, and now that i have it, i am not going to be silent" - madeleine albright.

#feminism #equity #equality #humanrights #dogood #metoo #fairness #onelove #womenshealth

text:
a canadian man told me that men are capable of handling excess amount of alcohol, they are psychologically and genetically strong in handling alcohol but women are not. yesterday, i saw a beautiful dutch art by jacob savery in the art gallery of alberta that shows men going crazy, brawling and vomiting (in the lower left corner of the painting) while their wives are trying to control and restrain them. it takes even more psychological, mental and physical effort to control a drunk alcoholic man than it takes to handle alcohol. every individual has their own capability of handling alcohol, some women can handle more alcohol than men. anybody can feel sick and mad when it comes to excess alcohol, doesn't matter if it's a man or a woman. .
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
my hair started falling out in clumps after my flashback nightmares started when i was 19 years old. my hair had always shed some strands, but it increased dramatically to handfuls at a time. as a child and teen, people often raved about my thick shiny hair over my sun kissed skin. being a kid who tried to excel at everything, i loved that my hair didnâ€™t require anything to be noticeable. it was just me being me without any striving. i loved the ease of not needing to comb it or tend to it. my hair was an area of my being that felt best if untouched. free to be beautiful.

losing my hair while being tormented by flashbacks felt as if i was forced to sacrifice yet another part of me to the trauma. shame heaping on shame. and for me, shame turns quickly to hopelessness. so i cut my long shiny locks my freshman year of college hoping that short hair would mean less stress. it didnâ€™t work. flashbacks remained and hair still fell out. i learned to ignore it, excuse it, neglect it, and tolerate it. it was okay enough, long enough, short enough, clean enough. enough hair to exist, but not the childlike freedom and ease i had once enjoyed. the less attention i paid my hair, the less i had to think about why it fell out.

what i didnâ€™t know then (that i know now) is trauma triggers autoimmune chaos. my body was holding a level of suffering and torment it wasnâ€™t designed to store. what i needed was to shed tears for the atrocity done to me, but because i didnâ€™t know how to do that, i think i shed copious amounts of hair instead. 
this year i celebrate a decade of intentional trauma healing and major physical health milestones. i healed many of my autoimmune issues. and guess what else? my hair stopped falling out. and it grows thick and fast like itâ€™s finally free to do what itâ€™s always been made to do. and i get a big smile every time someone sees me now and says â€œi canâ€™t believe your hair. itâ€™s so long and full. itâ€™s gorgeous!â€ oh yes. yes, it is. ğŸ˜‰
the little girl inside me who is learning to find her freedom again joyfully agrees. ğŸ¦‹

text:
ironman arizona 2015
3 years ago today ğŸ™ğŸ½
â€¢
here is a little bit from my journal entry about crossing that first ironman finish line:
â€¢
triumph.
maybe the only word i can use to describe this moment. overwhelming light and triumph.
â€¢
this finish line was more symbolic of life to me than simply a race. three years agoâ€¦the same tearsâ€¦the same hands holding my faceâ€¦but it was a different girlâ€¦that girl was lying on the bathroom floor.
her truth was thisâ€¦unlovedâ€¦uninterestingâ€¦undesirableâ€¦untalentedâ€¦un-strongâ€¦unworthy.
â€¢
unless you have lived those truths to the point where it isnâ€™t a fleeting thought it is yourÂ beliefÂ of yourself you canâ€™t understand the depths that it takes to undo those beliefs. i donâ€™t see any of those qualities anymore in this girl. but it was a battle to the darkness of hell and back to reach my new truthsâ€¦
lovedâ€¦interestingâ€¦desirableâ€¦talentedâ€¦strongâ€¦worthy.
â€¢
this race was for that girl.
i dedicate it to that girl who three short years ago was shedding the same tears on her bathroom floor and never in a bazillion light years could envision this moment happening. never. but it did.
â€¢
and it was a battle of highs and lows on the ironman arizona course just as it was a battle in life. the biggest take away from this race is a new truth. 
a profound and simple truthâ€¦
â€¢
the finish line is actually the start line
â€¢
here is to lifeâ€¦loveâ€¦adventureâ€¦miraclesâ€¦magicâ€¦and all the wonders this universe, god and angels have in storeâ€¦life is for living. so get out there and live.
â€¢
because if i can do thisâ€¦anyone can. and that means you.
â€¢

text:
kesenjangan nilai kontrak aktris perempuan dan laki-laki tidak hanya dialami oleh hollywood. di bollywood pun demikian, dengan rentang jarak nilai yang sangat jauh berbeda antara aktor dan aktrisnya.

namun hal itu tidak dialami olehÂ abhishek bachchanÂ danÂ aishwarya rai. tanpa tedeng aling-aling, abhishek mengungkap bahwa selama ini bayaran yang ia terima kerap kali lebih sedikit daripada nilai kontrak aishwarya rai. "dari sembilan film yang kubintangi bersamanya, delapan di antaranya aishwarya dibayar lebih mahal daripada aku," ujar abhishek seperti dilansir dari pinkvilla.com.

1. ibu abhishek juga dibayar lebih mahal

lebih lanjut, putra bungsu amitabh bachchan dan jaya bachchan ini juga menyebut bahwa ibunya pun dibayar lebih mahal daripada dirinya. meski tidak selalu, namun dalam beberapa kesempatan nilai kontrak jaya bachchan lebih tinggi daripada kontraknya.

abhishek menilai, kesenjangan nilai kontrak yang selama ini jadi perdebatan di india tidak berlaku di keluarganya. ia bisa menerima mengapa aishwarya dibayar lebih mahal, dan mengapa aktris lain juga dibayar lebih mahal daripada dirinya atau ayahnya. "deepika padukone dibayar lebih mahal daripada ayahku di film piku. kalau kamu punya kualitas yang mumpuni, bayaran tinggi akan mengikuti. tapi kalau baru terjun ke dunia film, jangan berharap dapat bayaran sebanyak shahrukh khan," ujarnya.

2. ingin perempuan diperlakukan sama

secara garis besar, abhishek mengungkap bahwa ia ingin semua orang di dunia memperlakukan pria dan wanita dengan setara. sebagai seorang pria yang memiliki kakak perempuan dan seorang anak perempuan, abhishek melihat betapa pentingnya kesetaraan.

kini, ketika india ramai dengan gerakan #metoo, abhishek pun menilainya secara positif. ia berharap dengan banyaknya perempuan yang bersuara dalam gerakan ini, kesetaraan dan keadilan akan segera jadi kenyataan di india. .
.
.
source by : kapanlagi
.
.

text:
exposure to and the experience of trauma has been a part of the human condition since we evolved as a species. we are all impacted by cyclical acts of violence. however, there continues to be a paralysis in the conversation following human trauma. the recent national dialogue surrounding trauma, especially sexual violence, has proven that as a society and culture, many simply donâ€™t understand or know how to talk about the aftermath of traumaâ€¦without shaming, blaming, invalidating, or placing the survivor on trial
.
.
trauma, in its many forms, is more than a singular event, but a force that firmly roots itself and can unravel many layers in a survivor's life. the aftermath of trauma can be more devastating and debilitating than the trauma itself. trauma does not remain still and moves with force and has the powerful capacity to reshape who we are, view of self and others, roles, relationships, the ability to cope, the ability to parent, and how we navigate through the world.
.
.
hey trauma, the day we met is an anonymous postcard project that allows survivors, as well those impacted by vicarious/secondary trauma (family, friends, or partners of survivors), to step out of the shadows of silence and give voice to how their lives changed....the day they met trauma. .
.
. ~dr. tama lane
.
.

text:
tomorrow is the day, maui babes! ğŸŒ´ğŸ–ğŸŒŠ
.
in case this is the first youâ€™ve heard of it, tomorrow the pearl projects (portland, or) and noonday collection (worldwide) are hosting a gathering in haiku for local women!
.
our purpose in putting together this gathering is to offer a time of storytelling and friendship.ğŸ’™
.
the stories that we will present offer a thread that connects us to other women all over the world and to women in our own communities.
.
the pearl projects and noonday collection share a passion to see women flourish in every aspect of their lives. that is what this thing is all about.
the stories weâ€™ll share have everything to do with the idea that when one woman flourishes, that she can effect true healing and change in her community.
.
we all want to be a part of something bigger than ourselves. noonday collection and the pearl projects offer a few ways to do that:
the pearl projects create resources and opportunities for women to gather together, to learn about god together, and to serve their communities in practical ways, together.
the pearl projects address some of the most pressing issues facing women today such as: what now, after #metoo (after sexual trauma). and how do i find meaningful connection with other women in my community? how can i help to make an impact on women locally in the sex industry? how can i let me lifeâ€™s story become a tool for shaping my future?
.
noonday collection uses fashion (beautiful handmade jewelry) to create meaningful opportunities for artisans around the world. they empower women with dignified jobs so that the women thrive in their local economies. that means that children are cherished and prioritized (families thrive), and we get to be connected to their stories.
.
come connect with us and see noonday's line of fashion-forward jewelry and precious christmas giftables. hear from @jenna__hays (founder of the pearl projects) as she offers the beautiful stories that these two organizations represent.
.
can you come? 
consider this gathering tomorrow night to be causal, fun, and soul nourishing. great food and drinks and stellar company! ğŸ˜ 7-9pm â€”>

text:
the swan, no. 1 by hilma af klint
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
this painting made me cry. it is as exhausting to be a survivor in the #metoo era as it is empowering. iâ€™m trying my damnedest to open up the windows, and address the dark so that i may stand more firmly grounded in the light. i was raped when i was in college. my health, grades, and happiness deteriorated. i was a real shitshow for a couple of years. there are parts of me i canâ€™t get back, and parts that are a little bent now.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
iâ€™ve had two poems accepted for publication in the #yanyr anthology, and i am so humbled, and so raw about it, and so proud to be where i am now. the editors at @rhythmboneslit created something momentous in giving survivors a platform to share art created out of such living, breathing grief. the you are not your rape anthology is heavy, and itâ€™s necessary. writing about having been assaulted has been heavy and necessary. this isnâ€™t my first publication, but it will be the first one in print, and i couldnâ€™t be more honored, or excited to soon hold this book in my hands. â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
i am not my fucking rape. i am more than that unspeakable trespass against me. i am changed, but i am still here. â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
yanyr now available for preorder, link in my bio.

text:
i have a great question for you today.  to what extent are you willing to challenge yourself?
is there something that you really want to do, but are afraid?
well today i challenge you to challenge yourself.  think of just one thing youâ€™ve wanted to do, but have been hesitating, procrastinating or just too fearful.
-â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
this is the pic of me exactly two years ago. i met someone who was traveling to ireland and this was a place iâ€™ve always wanted to go.  when i shared with him how envious i was, he said just book a flight and come!  oh sure...just book a flight.  i thought, who does that?  well, i did!  i booked a flight and in less than a week i was off to ireland!  talk about taking a leap of faith!  was i scared? hell, yes! but was it exhilarating? hell, yes! 
and not only did i fly to ireland on a whim, but here i am standing on the cliffs of moher almost 4 miles out! it was the most amazing life changing experience! (more about my ireland story in my book ğŸ˜Š)
-â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
so today i encourage you to do one thing - big or small and take that leap of faith!  every day is a gift and life is far too precious for us not to take that leap or make that change that will bring us the joy we are seeking.  so stop playing it safe!  what can you do today, that will help you grow and test your limits?
-â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
donâ€™t hide behind fear of failure or the shadow of your potential.  find out what your capable of! i never knew i was capable of walking four miles on the edge of a cliff with no safety barrier in ireland!  it all begins with that first step!  whoâ€™s with me?  whoâ€™s ready?  xo

text:
breaking news: sanford heisler sharp, llp, today filed a $70 million title ix individual and class action lawsuit against dartmouth college trustees for ignoring more than a decade of sexual harassment and abuse complaints from female students in its department of psychology and brain science. the plaintiffs allege a hostile academic culture of sexual misconduct, underage drinking and blatant disrespect for women was created by three tenured male professors, who were allowed to retire or resign this july, but the toxic conditions have not been remedied. pictured are the plaintiffs: andrea courtney, annemarie brown, kristina rapuano, marissa evans, sasha brietzke, and vassiki chauhan.

breaking news: sanford heisler sharp, llp, today filed a $70 million title ix individual and class action lawsuit against dartmouth college trustees for ignoring more than a decade of sexual harassment and abuse complaints from female students in its department of psychology and brain science. the plaintiffs allege a hostile academic culture of sexual misconduct, underage drinking and blatant disrespect for women was created by three tenured male professors, who were allowed to retire or resign this july, but the toxic conditions have not been remedied. pictured are the plaintiffs: andrea courtney, annemarie brown, kristina rapuano, marissa evans, sasha brietzke, and vassiki chauhan.

text:
this morning as i got on the subway i almost immediately received this request for an airdrop on my phone. of course, wanting to respect privacy, i declined immediately without even reading it. it then continued to pop up on my phone a few more times before i finally read what it said. i declined again, thinking maybe someone was talking to a friend in some sort of joking manner (ğŸ¤ğŸ»). then another one came through stating â€œyou gay bitch??â€ mind you, i have a rainbow pin on my backpack so at this point i realize this person is in fact targeting me. it also became chillingly clear that, as i had my back to the last row of seats on this car, this person was also within just 10 feet of me. i declined again and the same message popped up a few more times, each time i continued to decline. then another message, this time reading â€œfor real bitch how much to give me headâ€. this one came through multiple times and then another message â€œstop declining bitchâ€. i had two more stops to go at that point and it was all i could do to hold my shit together just to make it to my station. and then what about when i got off the train? would they follow me? am i safe? even as iâ€™m writing this, my heart is beating just as hard as it was in that moment. this is a very clear form of sexual harassment. iâ€™m sure i am not the first one this person has done this to and will not be the last. and who knows what else this person would have done or could be capable of doing in the future, or has already done in the past. sexual harassment/assault comes in so many forms and each experience affects that person in a unique way. there is no excuse for this, there is no â€œexplaining it awayâ€ or just looking past it and pretending like it didnâ€™t happen. this. shit. happens. every. day. when is it going to fucking stop?

text:
so honoured to be asked to speak out in london next year.

for years i would hide in my past too ashamed to speak, to ashamed to be me, to ashamed to live sometimes.

this was a part of my life that i kept secret for a long time, fearful, scared, lost oh so lost.  i wanted to just bury it, bury it deep down somewhere so i didn't have to look at that part of myself ever again.  the shame i felt nearly burying me alive.

gratefully i am learning to stand proud.  i am learning to stand strong. 
before i entered this world i was already a lost scared child looking for love, looking for acceptance, family in whatever form i could find it in. 
i was vunerable and i was not in a place emotionally, spiritually or physically where i thought i had a choice.  i thought this was the only road that was for me.  this was the only road i could see.

and so began my life down this dark scary path.

i am grateful i have found my voice.  i am grateful that this once dark  path i could only see and once walked,  i can now walk down again,  but this time, this time i get to walk this path linking arms with others .... this time i get to  carry a huge big fucking light with me  and hold it so high, that it lights the paths of choice , love and hope for others to see who still reside in the darkness. <3 
#believesurvivors #believewomen #metoo #womenofcolour ##empowerwomen #standtogether #speakout #findyourvoice #nomoresecrets #nomoreshame #standforwomen #standwithme #standwithally

â €
one the show blythe shares some of her own abuse and how the #metoo movement and dressember are intersecting for so many women around the world. â €
â €
if you want some practical things to do this year to help end human trafficking, this episode is going to give you what you need! â €
â €

text:
tess paras @tessparas is an actor, writer, director, producer based in los angeles. known for her roles on crazy ex-girlfriend, grimm, take my wife, tess is now creating her own space and is discussing her personal experiences. her current project, @thepatientsfilm , is a film about a filipino american immigrant family that is learning to heal through trauma in the time of the #metoo movement. the patients tackles the subject of a young woman who experienced a â€œbad fightâ€ and the subsequent repercussions. it shares the story of relationships within the family, coping, seeking help, and supporting each other. an inclusive film, the patients holds a fil am main cast and a diverse supporting cast, with a crew behind the camera that are women, persons identifying as lgbtqia, and/or aapi. this is about sharing asian american and filipino american experiences that are not always told, validating our community, and being seen. to support, check the link below and read more about tess and her work. 
tess is driven and strong, taking up space and telling her stories. 
#intheheartstories #pinay #thepatientsfilm #filam #filipinoamerican

i've watched the qspiracy since the start.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the bombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing for the 2016 election.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the content and more or less fake accounts - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking the responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole thing is build on the same user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

and here comes the best part. trumq is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words.

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

#fastfashion #dior #highfashion #jenniferlawrence #fuckfashionthatcolonizes
#decolonizefashion #workit
#reparations #decolonize #create #imagine #resist

first, there is no one method or formula for determining reparations.

so much of the violence we experience is personalized. the violence we experience is always shared by other people and communities, yet how it affects us is embodied and related to who we are in this #earth walk. that's why this method was designed for people like you and #metoo and #decolonizethisplace. 
second, calculating reparations is always an economic and #spiritual practice.

above all, the spiritual dimension of this method is central, and #survivors must lead each initiative. the point is to foster #healing, not pay for therapy and legal costs, and give people the support we require to create solutions for ourselves and our #beloved communities. so, what does healing mean for you as a survivor of the violence you seek to stop? given your daily life and needs at this time, what do you need to put in place to learn and apply the method?

from a purely economic perspective, what aspects of healing can financial reparations facilitate? this question is the most direct, but it isn't as simple as it sounds. for example, you might #desire therapy and know that therapists cost a rate of, say $60-250 an hour in your town. what if no therapist in your local beloved community speaks your mother language of #zapotec or #lakota or #quechua and that's the language in which you sense the world? what is the #honest price tag for your therapy sessions if you have to travel three hours to see a therapist who shares your cultural, linguistic, #ancestral #perspective?

what else is at play when it comes to money? emotions such as grief and anger, fear and pain, shame and guilt always bubble to the surface when delving into traumatic experiences, and poverty is its own trauma. what can make this learning process a means of healing financial trauma in your personal life and that of your beloved community?
name: darshan elena campos

text: ywca new britain's sexual assault crisis service (sacs) covers a 46-town region - all of hartford county, part of tolland county and the town of plymouth. we offer assistance to sexual assault survivors and their loved ones. these services are critical after such trauma, helping victims and their families regain feelings of independence, optimism, and hope. the advocates on staff are trained to work with hospital staff, the court system, public safety officers and other counselors assisting their clients. you can call our 24-hour english and spanish confidential hotlines for immediate access to trained, certified counselors anytime. #sacs#sexualtassaultcrisisservice #metoo #hotline #crisishotline #webelieveyou

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
#loveitall

all the ups, downs, breaks and put-back-togethers.
each crack makes you who you are at this moment. 
it may provide you with empathy and understanding. 
it may create the great listener that you are.
it provides patience and support.  maybe even forgiveness.
it creates a lot of other things that are a part of us too...but for now, let's remember the good.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
it was bannonâ€™s interest in culture as war that ignited wylieâ€™s intellectual concept. but it was robert mercerâ€™s millions that created a firestorm. kogan was able to throw money at the hard problem of acquiring personal data: he advertised for people who were willing to be paid to take a personality quiz on amazonâ€™sÂ mechanical turkÂ andÂ qualtrics. at the end of which koganâ€™s app, called thisismydigitallife, gave him permission to access their facebook profiles. and not just theirs, but their friendsâ€™ too. on average, each â€œseederâ€ â€“ the people who had taken the personality test, around 320,000 in total â€“ unwittingly gave access to at least 160 other peopleâ€™s profiles, none of whom would have known or had reason to suspect.

what the email correspondence between cambridge analytica employees and kogan shows is that kogan had collected millions of profiles in a matter of weeks. but neither wylie nor anyone else at cambridge analytica had checked that it was legal. it certainly wasnâ€™t authorised. kogan did have permission to pull facebook data, but for academic purposes only. whatâ€™s more, under british data protection laws, itâ€™s illegal for personal data to be sold to a third party without consent.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
blood diamond_maddy bowen (2/2) happy #monologuethursday folks! as the holiday season approaches, i feel like it gets even easier to get detached from the reality of the world around us - you know, everything sparkles and smells of cinnamon and we want to lose ourselves in that magic, beautiful, happy world that doesn't really exist. which is fine, don't get me wrong. but still. being my other job in the fashion industry i see this stuff all the year around, and sometimes i feel the need to bring things back to reality.
wether it's fur, or diamonds, or anything that implies beauty being at the cost of someone else's happiness, freedom, or life, we should take a moment and really look through that beautiful, yet deadly thing. and maybe, ask ourselves if there isn't another way to make the world function. because there must be. 
love,
#agirlfromtheislandinnewyork

text:
thank you  @cristina_the_activist - your words are crystal clear to those who are capable of hearing and for those with a conscience. the others will unfollow or spew some righteous, guilt-fueled vitriol. itâ€™s expected of the weak. this post is for those open to change and embracing a life devoid of cruelty and torture. thank you, in advance for being open to allowing the compassion to drop in. we are what we eat. their suffering only becomes our own. think about it. ğŸ–¤ğŸ–¤ğŸ–¤â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”i snuck onto a noosa dairy farm yesterday. i wanted to see the babies with my own eyes. from afar it looked like the crates were empty but as i got closer and looked inside, there were day old babies huddled inside. it was 20 degrees out, had been snowing all night and here they were by themselves in the cold. so many of them were absolutely terrified of me - others would run up and start sucking on my fingers just hoping i was their mother.
some of them will be used in the dairy industry because they are considered profitable - others will be killed not too long from now so someone can eat their fragile body. 
this is animal agriculture.
it is not hard work, it is not a good job - it is selling your soul to profit off of others. 
it is separating families to make money off of their flesh. 
it is raping animals with your own two hands to keep their blood line going to keep your pockets full. 
it is mutilating babies and calling it normal and necessary. 
it is creating families, only to pull them apart.
the animal industry is nothing to glorify, it is nothing to be proud of. 
it is slavery and ultimately death.
this child does not belong here, but someone is paying to make this happen.. is it you?

text:
mgtow 101: personality tests

there are a few questions and scenarios leaders can use to find out how the members in their group think. let's say you are seeking a co partner, assistant, partnership or manager, rather than asking the same scripted questions, you can ask questions which shows a persons ability to think out the box as well as vet their ability to comprehend information. you can also get an inside look to their subconscious without them getting a sense that you are judging them.

examples:

1) if you could have super powers, which would you have?

2) if you won't the lottery what would you do with it?

3) who is the greatest predator to the human, shark or lion?

4) the question in the meme above, red pill vs blue pill?

all of these questions are fun ways to find out how deeply a person thinks, without them feeling defensive about the questions. these questions may seem simple but it will literally give you insights to the depths of the mind, no matter how deep or shallow.

as an example, if i asked the question to a group of 30 people, i would easily be able to eliminate anyone who answered blue pill for a partnership, because it would show a lack of depth and comprehension. with the knowledge we all have today, everyone could be a billionaire if they could take the current knowledge with you into the past.

a simple person would say knowledge is just what you learned by being educated. however an outside the box thinker could look at it and pull a back to the future move, taking the almanac, championship winning teams and lottery numbers back in the past with you. you could even set yourself up to be viewed as a god on earth by predicting all types of events like 9/11, presidential elections, terrorist attacks, natural disasters and much more. these questions show how deep one is able to think.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

jon sharman

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green, author
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green, author
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

.
.
.
we have become a people pitted one against the other. invisible is the line that divides us, but the chasm is vast and wide â€“ for we cannot speak, we cannot listen, nor imagine bridging the gap between ourselves and the â€œotherâ€ on that side. the struggle of our time is to bridge that gap, and we are none of us immune to it.

we see battles springing up on every corner of the horizon, and among them is one catalyzed by a great rage building in the hearts of the women in this land. one in three of us has suffered rape, assault, abuse or physical violation of some kind. one in three of us has a story to tell of a burden we are bearing. the stories vary, as do the many ways in which we are wounded, and until now they have mostly been stories we keep to ourselves.

until now. .
.

text:
the one with a danish journey. 
two years ago, i had the extraordinary experience to meet people so talented, honest, truthful and intelligent. they inspired me and made me fight for what is right. 
our life has changed so much since we walked together. and now, it is time to remember the moment when i found the fire that they are, those eyes that make me see myself so different.

text:
Â« p o e m Â»
.
.
.
sometimes, it will go by too fast 
and you will struggle to keep up with it 
but don't worry, it won't last long 
and you'll be know how to resist your own emotions 
and take control over what's already yours 
the word will sting, darling, but trust me 
and listen closely-
it's not over yet, 
the path to your life is still right ahead
even if it's dark, just light your fire 
and watch the world burn for you
.
.
// ayesha fatimah
.
.
.

text:
the one with a danish journey. 
two years ago, i had the extraordinary experience to meet people so talented, honest, truthful and intelligent. they inspired me and made me fight for what is right.

text:
first, there is no one method or formula for determining #reparations.

so much of the #violence we experience is personalized. the violence we experience as individuals is always shared by other people and communities, yet how it affects us is embodied and related to who we are in this earth walk. that's why this method was designed for people like you and #metoo.

second, calculating reparations is always an economic and #spiritual practice.

above all, the spiritual dimension of this method is central, and #survivors must lead each initiative. the point is to foster #healing, not pay for therapy and legal costs, and give people the support we require to #create #solutions for ourselves and our #beloved communities. so, what does healing mean for you as a #survivor of the violence you seek to stop? given your daily life and needs at this time, what do you need to put in place to #learn and #apply the method?

from a purely economic #perspective, what aspects of healing can financial reparations facilitate? this question is the most direct, but it isn't as simple as it sounds. for example, you might desire therapy and know that therapists cost a rate of, say $60-250 an hour in your town. what if no therapist in your local beloved community speaks your mother language of quechua and that's the language in which you sense the world? what is the honest price tag for your therapy sessions if you have to #travel three hours to see a therapist who shares your #cultural, #linguistic, #ancestral perspective?

text: "this countryâ€¦ needsâ€¦ no thin idealist, no coarse realist, but a man whose eye reads the heavens, while his feet step firmly on the ground, and his hands are strong and dexterous for the use of human implementsâ€¦ a man of universal sympathies, but self-possessed; a man who knows the region of emotion, though he is not its slave; a man to whom this world is no mere spectacle or fleeting shadow, but a great, solemn game, to be played with good heed, for its stakes are of eternal value, yet who, if his play be true, heeds not what he loses by the falsehood of others; a man who hives from the past, yet knows that its honey can but moderately avail him; whose comprehensive eye scans the present, neither infatuated by its golden lures, nor chilled by its many ventures; who possesses prescience, the gift which discerns tomorrow â€” when there is such a man for #america, the thought which urges her on will be expressed." -margaret fuller

text:
i love the kind of poems
where we donâ€™t speak to each other

there are airport lounges in the scene, 
beach-side restaurants and
birthday parties of mutual friends

but

itâ€™s the hotel elevators
where conversations happen
when we try to go for the buttons
and our fingers touch

itâ€™s the queues for groceries
where we stand behind one another
and accidentally take a step too soon
or one too late

itâ€™s picking the same book
taking the same taxi
or sitting next to each other at the movies, 
our legs tight for the shiver, 
where our worlds coexist 
for a little while

the tension that builds between us in rooms
is the tickle i take to bed at nights

with my eyes closed, my fingers
draw me to depths of dreams
where we canâ€™t stop talking dirty

and i end up not knowing what to feel
for you except that i know exactly
how i donâ€™t want to

so each day i think of a hundred ways
to spark a conversation with you, 
yet each night, end up closing
with a poem where

we donâ€™t speak to each other.
.
.
animesh ganguly.
(@penningdownthemind)
.
.
.

text:
you might think i am crazy ğŸ˜œ 
well i am a little crazy ğŸ˜ 
i decided to start my 80 day program again this morning... what? why? how?
.
you may ask,how on earth do you think you will have time to do this? .
why would you start a commitment like that a week before thanksgiving ğŸ¦ƒ  and during christmas ğŸ„?
.
well...there is never a good time to start. i want to workout during this time of year. this makes it easy because i have a daily plan. a check list to stick to. .
maybe i make one less batch of cookies, maybe i use gift bags instead of wrapping paper, maybe my house wonâ€™t be perfect ğŸ‘Œ that is ok i will be happier if i take care of myself!! .
it is never a good time to start new plan but that is life and if you can be successful when life is crazy you will be wicked successful all the time!!!

as i look at this candid capture taken during filming on monday, i wonder what i couldâ€™ve possibly been thinking...and iâ€™m pretty sure i was having a conversation with myself that went something like this: â€œwow leah, you made it! i mean, you really really made it! just a few years ago you were living in a 200 square foot room, with every ounce of what you owned tucked into the trunk of your car. you were living in fear, fleeing and hiding from a sadistic abuser who refused to let you go. constantly watching over your shoulder, afraid to walk outside alone, looking around every corner, wondering what may happen next, jumping at every loud noise late at night, praying that the stalking would stop. praying that sheâ€™d stop trying to break in. praying that i wouldnâ€™t suddenly disappear and become a news statistic. that was your rock bottom...you lost everything, you cried yourself to sleep every night, in a constant state of fear-induced survival. but look at you now! did you ever in a million years think that this is where youâ€™d be? safe, healed, stronger and happier than youâ€™ve ever been? no, you didnâ€™t expect this, but guess what? this is real. this is your life. this is your truth. you glow girl.â€ what a difference time makes.
what a difference healing makes.
what a difference survival makes.
what a difference resilience makes!

text:
producer plug:  this three day event is a gift from playwright alyson mead, who in the wake of conversations about consent, sexual assualt and rape has graciously given special permission to perform her timely play "the flora and fauna" across the nation. 
omaha was given permission to perform this show three times, in hopes to reach the wider community. 
all tickets have a $10 suggested donation and all proceeds go to benefit the #metoo movement as we work tirelessly to end sexual assault and rape culture. get tickets at the link here: 
https://www.eventbrite.com/e/the-flora-and-the-fauna-tickets-52185287600

this event features 18 of omaha's finest actors, and we could've cast it 3 times over with the overwhelming support and love we've received from local talent.

reserve your tickets now. share the event. carpool. bring your mothers, husbands, sisters and sons to watch brilliant performances of this searing and honest play. 
the flora and fauna by alyson mead
directed by amy lane and beth thompson
produced by beaufield berry-fisher
with special thanks to steven williams, valerie st. pierre smith and carol danigle.

text:
tomorrow is #whiteribbonday in greater cleveland! the white ribbon campaign offers men, boys, and people of any gender identity an opportunity to speak out against violence and publicly promote healthy relationships.
.
to participate, you can 1. attend the public rally tomorrow at noon on the steps of the cuyahoga county domestic relations courthouse. 2. wear a white ribbon or tie. 3. talk to youth in your life about the meaning of consent. 4. recruit your friends and family to participate.
.

text:
blood diamond_maddy bowen (1/2) happy #monologuethursday folks! as the holiday season approaches, i feel like it gets even easier to get detached from the reality of the world around us - you know, everything sparkles and smells of cinnamon and we want to lose ourselves in that magic, beautiful, happy world that doesn't really exist. which is fine, don't get me wrong. but still. being my other job in the fashion industry i see this stuff all the year around, and sometimes i feel the need to bring things back to reality.
wether it's fur, or diamonds, or anything that implies beauty being at the cost of someone else's happiness, freedom, or life, we should take a moment and really look through that beautiful, yet deadly thing. and maybe, ask ourselves if there isn't another way to make the world function. because there must be. 
love,
#agirlfromtheislandinnewyork

text:
lately (lol the past 3 yrs) iâ€™ve been doubting whether i did the right thing choosing film school over business school. like iâ€™ve always been into film and wanting to work in the film industry and coming out of high school the last thing i wanted was to do three years of econometrics, statistics and fiscal policies. but now nearing the end of my degree in film i feel like maybe i shouldâ€™ve suffered thru that and having kept my passion for film as a hobby. then i realized damn thereâ€™re probably so many people out there studying business & economics with an interest in film but the number of people studying film interested in business & economics are definitely a lot fewer. and what i love about studying film and having business & economics as like a â€œhobby interestâ€ is that i get to have a passion about something that a lot of people think are boring and odd to have a passion for as an art student. i guess what iâ€™m saying is maybe i wouldâ€™ve regretted it too if i chose an economics degree 3 yrs ago, and that thereâ€™ll always be several pathways to reach your goals and none of them are gonna be right or wrong. donâ€™t you think? 
did a lil youtube video on the topic, check it out! link in bio. â¤ï¸

#throwbackthursday to this time last year. i was desperately unhappy and in a cycle of self-destructive behaviour that not only affected me and my wellbeing, but that of others as well. i did a lot of things in 2017 iâ€™m not proud of and i honestly believed for a long time that nothing would ever get better, that i wouldnâ€™t make it to 30 because everything was too much. in january of this year, i attempted to end my life, and was later sexually assaulted by a stranger. my family was falling apart around me and my life just felt like it was spiralling out of my control, no matter how hard i fought. iâ€™m not saying everything is perfect now - i donâ€™t like my appearance and have ongoing familial issues - but iâ€™ve just accepted a job in a place that makes me feel genuinely happy for the first time in my life. i donâ€™t feel powerless to the demons in my head or the whims of others anymore. i am my own woman, the woman i thought iâ€™d lost. thereâ€™s still a long way to go, but iâ€™ve taken some very serious steps towards being the person i want to be. and iâ€™m proud of myself for that. .
.
.
.
.

text:
**please read**
i don't normally use my buisness as a platform to get political. however today i am. 
the beautiful women pictured here is my husbands aunt. she was brutally and coldly murdered by her husband in 2001 who was sentance to life in prison in 2002 for first degree murder. i never had the chance to meet aunt shelley but ever since i started dating my husband 12 years ago i have felt her presence in the family. she was the laughter and light of his family. she still is today even though shes not with us.

my mother in law recently did some digging into the status of aunt shelley's murderer and found out he was in a minimum security prison that is dorm style. he has monthly escorted leaves from prison...and is married with a daughter! he was charge with first degree murder becuase he planned out her murder for days and ended her life in a stomach turning and horrific manner. he should be in maximum security prison with no access to the public for everyones safety. our family had no idea about this information until one month ago and we are outraged. 
we are going public with this information in the hope to change the correction system in canada and to plead with the public that if you had a loved one murdered to check on their killers status in prison. because the punishment should fit the crime. honestly canada...if this evil man didn't remain in a maximum security prison, what do you have to do to remain there?

in the link.tree link in my bio you will find a link to the cbc article that explains everything in even more depth. however i warn you the article is graphic and heart breaking. but its a story that needs to be told so hopefully change can happen. i pray some of my 560 instagram and 180 facebook followers will read the article and help our family spread the word about this injustice. 
thank you for reading this caption. there is so much more i could say but the cbc article truely says it all. â™¡ kaitlyn *
*
*
#justice #fightforjustice #canadiangovernment #metoo

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the companyâ€™s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when youâ€™re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a personâ€™s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the â€œtraining setâ€ refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your â€œfeature setâ€: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, itâ€™s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data â€“ the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that youâ€™re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the companyâ€™s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when youâ€™re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a personâ€™s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the â€œtraining setâ€ refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your â€œfeature setâ€: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, itâ€™s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data â€“ the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that youâ€™re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the companyâ€™s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when youâ€™re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a personâ€™s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the â€œtraining setâ€ refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your â€œfeature setâ€: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, itâ€™s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data â€“ the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that youâ€™re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when youâ€™re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a personâ€™s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the â€œtraining setâ€ refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most impoant, it needs to contain your â€œfeature setâ€: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, itâ€™s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data â€“ the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that youâ€™re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

text:
one year later *** dear benjamin brenner gerard (the one who sexually assaulted me),
i forgive you. you do not deserve to be held in my thoughts. you do not deserve to remain immortal in my fears. i forgive you for being weak. i forgive you for being the person you are, the child you will never grow out of, and the delusions you hold. i will never stop defending myself, however i will stop allowing you to have any remaining power over me. i forgive you for allowing your parents to hire a horrible lawyer to protect their 26 year old child. i forgive you for having faults that leads you to needing to force yourself upon others. i forgive you for being so weak and insecure that sexual assault is the way you pretend to have power. i forgive you. thank you for creating a situation in which i learned how strong and intelligent i truly am.

penned from my self worth,
sophie stephen **

text:
today parents, advocates and caregivers go to the massachusetts state house to make nickyâ€™s law a reality.
.
our children/adult children are vulnerable to physical and sexual abuse. abuse cases are very difficult to prosecute and when the victim is unable to speak/testify well it is nearly impossible.

the boston globe highlighted to the 30% rise in abuse to this population. 
parents and advocates want their children to be safe and need to prevent abusers from returning to a job with this vulnerable population.
.
.
.
please learn about nickyâ€™s law and consider mobilization to create a law in your state. this is a national issue and we must all act now!
.
.
.
.
.

text: in aa i have been told to â€œturn it overâ€ every day i walk into the rooms or speak to a loving sponsor. i can say that humility has served me so well when it comes to my recovery and has allowed me my greatest asset!  to be vulnerable and never drink or drug!  my ego wants me to hide my true spirit, wants me to believe i can handle my drinking, i can quit after the next line or hit or whatever....the ego knows no love, only how to crave.  my ego brought me to these rooms at a young age because â€œi did it my wayâ€ stepping on everyone including myself.  i was broken because i had a false sense of ego driving my life that was insatiable.  i had no concept of god as i came to know him on my terms, he was never there to save me as a kid from all my trauma. i never stopped running long enough to consider that you guys were having these meetings and all i had to do was show up!  i stayed out of a longing robe loved and understood and quit using because my â€œlife had become unmanageableâ€ at 26 years old.  what i ended up learning was that i could face my entire lifetime of childhood trauma, mental illness, addiction in every area of my life and find a life of love, purpose and willingness to help others.  i still have to do the basics everyday, i check my ego at the door, pull up a chair and at the end of the day â€œmy name is laura, i am an alcoholic and an addict, i am so glad you are hereâ€  i love you, i really do because i have truly learned what unconditional love is.  #metooneveryou #theshamelesswarrior #aa #billw #alcoholicsanonymous #sobrietyismylove #sober #sobriety #sobrietyquotes #mentalhealth #mentalhealthawareness #mentalillness #traumahealing #bipolar #add #adhd #autismawareness #autism #recoveryispossible #recoveryisworthit #violenceagainstwomen #metoo #timesup

text:
i donâ€™t preach, i pretty much keep my political opinions to myself.  iâ€™m not the rock the boat type. you are entitled to your opinion, i am entitled to mine, i donâ€™t have to agree with yours and you donâ€™t have to agree with mine. 
but, #metoo is a valuable lesson everyone needs to learn from. everyone, not only women, should be able to come forward about something thatâ€™s happened to them without fear of retaliation.  nys has entered the movement requiring that all employees take part in a sexual harassment course.  everyone. thatâ€™s how important this is. 
the unfortunate lack of regulation so far basically letâ€™s anyone give this course as long as you meet the stateâ€™s criteria. the seminar i attended last night, i was appalled. (not set up by myself and i will give the benefit of the doubt that the individuals who set it up were unaware)

if your first anecdote on the #sexualharassment course you are giving is that â€œi was accused and i beat itâ€, we should have just stopped there. you are the epitome of why this movement was so important.  the rest of the presentation was appalling and the lack of care taken to put it together was beyond disappointing.  your job was to empower the attendees to have a voice, but you decided to spout your sad little story and shoot down the very event youâ€™re supposed to provide power to.

i hope people know that this one person does not represent the people who really do care about your safety and your ability to come forward and be heard and believed. i will always be a welcoming place to come should you need the shoulder to cry on or the shoulders to lift you up and empower the strength i know you have.

#shareyourstory #dontbeafraid #standstrong #empowerpeople #empowerwomen #bestrong

text:
we are entering the second edition of 16 film festival in conjunction with #16daysofactivism in the global movement to fight gender based violence. 
we hope to elevate the consciousness level and the courage through our 16 feature and 16 short films in our line up this year.
film adalah media yang ampuh untuk menggambarkan kejadian kejadian dalam masyarakat kita yang kerap bersentuhan dengan kekerasan berbasis gender dan seksualitas. lewat film kita melihat, mendengar, menumbuhkan rasa empati yang tak jarang berujung pada tumbuhnya kekuatan kolektif untuk mencari solusi dan memberantas kekerasan berbasis gender & seksualitas ini.

16 film festival terus berupaya membangun ruang ruang aman untuk berdidkusi, berekspresi, mencurahkan isi hati dan menciptakan support group yang memperkuat kesadaran kemanusiaan. 
meningkatnya angka kekerasan di negri ini memang memprihatinkan. tapi, bukan hal yang tidak mungkin, bahwa kenaikan angka tersebut diakibatkan kesadaran dan keberanian yang tumbuh sehingga setiap kasus meningkatkan kepedulian bersama.

saat ini keberpihakan pada korban lah yang harus diperjuangkan pada aparat dan institusi institusi formil. ruang 16 film festival pun terbuka bagi mereka-mereka yg duduk pada posisi krusial penegakan hukum negri ini.

ayo beranjak, dan turut hadir di 16 film festival! mulai tgl 25 mov -10 desember. besok kita akan jumpa pers dulu di @soulfood.id follow @enambelasffest untuk updatenya. #16filmfestival #zerotolerance #domesticviolence #genderviolence #hearmetoo #metoo #humanrights #womensright #activism #filmfestival #indonesia #komnasperempuan #16haktp #unaids #asv #viuindonesia

text:
be intentional....
with the holidays upon us, we will begin preparing for family gatherings and making sure we have all the right ingredients for a great meal. but, before you get too caught up in grocery shopping, pie baking, and table setting, be sure to start a dialogue with your child. take this opportunity to ask them how they feel about the various friends and family members they will likely be seeing at the upcoming family gathering and really listen to what they say about each individual. reiterate the concepts of boundaries and body autonomy. reassure them that they can come to you at anytime about anyone who makes them feel uncomfortable or touches them in any way that they don't like and you will listen to them and make it stop. being intentional in these discussions can help your child feel more comfortable telling you hard truths about the people you know and love without fear of not being heard or believed.  #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #sexcrimes #rapevictims #rape #victims #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate

"the idea for this book came to me as i was about to publish womenâ€™s anthology uncaged: the rise of the badass post #metoo. i was thinking about my then three-year-old son and wondering about the type of man he would grow up to be. i thought about my six-year-old daughter, contemplating how effective it would be raising a girl with a voice and clear boundaries if these couldnâ€™t protect her from the actions of those around her.

growing up i felt more connected to boys and men than i did girls and women; misogyny lives within us all, women too. yet i couldnâ€™t help observing the extent to which boys are also the victim of a deeply wounded, abusive culture."

text:
clothing is not consent 
why is it that the victim is always blamed ? i just don't get it. nobody asks to be raped, not by what they wear, who they hang around with or where they go. it's not the victims fault. our justice system is a sham for rape victims, humiliated in court and asked to show up underwear suggesting it may have given consent. underwear is evidence, evidence of the rape culture that exists in ireland. in ireland 42% of women have experienced sexual abuse, but only 10% was reported and only 8% of trials result in convictions. we need to come together, and try to change things 
i'm sure most of you have seen posts in the media recently surrounding rape and certain cases that have come up. if anyone's finding it difficult to deal with i can assure you you're not alone. my page is always open to anyone, sometimes a listening ear can do the world of good

text:
hello all, this year itm group of institutions will be celebrating international men's day on november 19, 2018 (monday). most people don't even know that there is, in fact, an internationally recognized day for men... and most people laugh at the idea of celebrating it. "isn't every day men's day?" is the common refrain.

we think that men should be acknowledged, recognized and celebrated... not just for their achievements and conquests, but for the roles they play in our society.

our theme this year is:
"hero ka hero"
- celebrating positive male role models

especially in light of the wave of #metoo allegations, and the spotlight that's been aimed at male behaviour, we must take the time to acknowledge that there are men who have been raised well, who treat everyone as equals and make us proud through how they live their lives.

so let's "remember the names of our fathers" and cherish the relationships we have with the men in our lives and our communities and celebrate international men's day!

#itmmovember 
#internationalmensday 
#comingsoon
#mensday 
#menshealthmatters 
#menmatter 
#men

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn
