is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
14-nov-2018: Â seminar on 'women of marginalised communities: concerns about exclusion' held in amu

aligarh, #november 14: #women have rights equal to that of men, but they continue to face disparity with unequal treatments and perceptions wholly or partly due to their gender, said prof zakia athar siddiqui, former director, advanced centre for women's studies, aligarh muslim university (amu), while delivering the keynote address in the indian council of social science research (icssr) sponsored national seminar on 'women of marginalised communities: concerns about exclusion' at the #arts faculty lounge.

in the seminar organised by the advanced centre for women's studies, prof zakia pointed out that we need to focus on how to help women to overcome vulnerabilities and shape their destinies in the national #growth story. "to help women of marginalised communities, we need to understand that equality for women is progress for all," she said adding that gender equality, women empowerment, women rights and the eradication of poverty are essential to economic and social development.

mr nizam pasha, advocate, supreme court of india said that women, across castes and classes, are marginalised, even if the degree varies. speaking on the #metoo movement, he pointed out that the campaign needs to have representations from dalit, bahujan, adivasi and other marginalised women. "let us build more resources and support for the most vulnerable and marginalised as any campaign should not treat the most vulnerable as just an afterthought," he said.

mr pasha also spoke on better enforcement of sexual harassment laws and setting up of tribunals for women in the informal sector.

quoting swami vivekananda, prof akbar husain, dean, faculty of social sciences said, "there is no chance of the welfare of the world unless the condition of women is improved." he pointed out, "women are all powerful if they have strong mind, confidence in their body language and maturity in handling relationships. empowerment is an internal attribute. a woman may feel empowered if she is contended with herself in physical, emotional, mental, social and spiritual terms."

i had a friend tell me once that it was her feeling that when people talk about what theyâ€™ve been through, they do it for attention or are playing the victim. imagine that. such backward thinking. as we grow, we no longer hold onto our â€œstoryâ€ or let our circumstances define us, and the stories simply become a way to help others through the pain of being stuck in a belief system that needs to change.*
*
each story is like a level in a video game: you arenâ€™t meant to get stuck on that level. youâ€™re meant to collect the tools you can and move on to the next level, so donâ€™t be afraid to share your stories. they will help someone who is in great pain figure out that what theyâ€™re going through is all a part of their growth as souls on this journey, nothing more. *
*
and if you are afraid to share your story because youâ€™re worried about what others will think of you, do some work around forgiving yourself and get to that deep level of understanding that this needs to be set free. we canâ€™t help others until weâ€™ve helped ourselves.*
*
_____

text:
minding the gap (2018)
.
minding the gap is a documentary thatâ€™s directed by bing liu. the film is about a
young men that bond together to escape volatile families in their rust-belt hometown. as three they face adult responsibilities, unexpected revelations threaten their decade-long friendship. it stars bing liu himself, kiere johnson, and zack mulligan.
.
this hulu documentary is one of the winners in sundance film festival. it win special jury award for breakthrough filmmaking. so, thereâ€™s no reason to not get hype watching the film. after watching the film, i must say that this film is one of the best film of 2018.
.
first of all, this film told bing liuâ€™s and his 2 friend story. so, this film tells a true story. the film is simply magnificent. the filmâ€™s story and the realism thatâ€™s told by 12 years of footage that greatly combined by bing liu is the driving force in the film. to be honest, i think itâ€™s one of the best documentary iâ€™ve watch.
.
the filmâ€™s camera work is beautiful. especially the footage that he made. like the use of fish eye, and the old camera back in the 90â€™s. it just transcend you to the video store generation. also, one of the example of the camera work that i love is when he shows us 2- 3 minutes of his friends skating through the town. i also want to give credit to the editing, 
and the way the truth unravel from the interview, so we can see the reaction and the emotion they all feel.
.
the problem that the film talk about is truly heart-breaking. abusive home is something that we hear people talk every day. but, to see their side of story, you couldnâ€™t avoid the thought of being lucky not to experience that. the film just make us fell sympathetic.
.
also, criticizing this film is kinda heart because, for me, documentary is like watching someone elseâ€™s memory, especially this film. the reason why i think this film is magnificent because i can see myself in one of the person in the film. relating to this film is very easy, and i think thatâ€™s the reason why people like this film.
.
grade : 9.3/10
.

harrassment of any form is wrong. be it physical or emotional. the idea of sex & consent are mutually exclusive. there canâ€™t be sex without consent. because sex without consent, is not sexâ€”itâ€™s rape, and rapes happen not only in work places , even in relationships and marriages.

whether you're speaking out as part of the #metoo movement or holding on to your story, every single person deserves to feel safe, happy and live past the physical/mental trauma they've been part of.

easier said than done, living in a society which keeps reminding us of the past we want to forget. key is to
 heal and understand that the past doesn't defile our honour nor define who we are, and what matters is how we want to live in the present, leading upto the future.

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the companyâ€™s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when youâ€™re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a personâ€™s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the â€œtraining setâ€ refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your â€œfeature setâ€: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, itâ€™s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data â€“ the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that youâ€™re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

14-nov-2018: Â seminar on 'women of marginalised communities: concerns about exclusion' held in amu

aligarh, #november 14: #women have rights equal to that of men, but they continue to face disparity with unequal treatments and perceptions wholly or partly due to their gender, said prof zakia athar siddiqui, former director, advanced centre for women's studies, aligarh muslim university (amu), while delivering the keynote address in the indian council of social science research (icssr) sponsored national seminar on 'women of marginalised communities: concerns about exclusion' at the #arts faculty lounge.

in the seminar organised by the advanced centre for women's studies, prof zakia pointed out that we need to focus on how to help women to overcome vulnerabilities and shape their destinies in the national #growth story. "to help women of marginalised communities, we need to understand that equality for women is progress for all," she said adding that gender equality, women empowerment, women rights and the eradication of poverty are essential to economic and social development.

mr nizam pasha, advocate, supreme court of india said that women, across castes and classes, are marginalised, even if the degree varies. speaking on the #metoo movement, he pointed out that the campaign needs to have representations from dalit, bahujan, adivasi and other marginalised women. "let us build more resources and support for the most vulnerable and marginalised as any campaign should not treat the most vulnerable as just an afterthought," he said.

mr pasha also spoke on better enforcement of sexual harassment laws and setting up of tribunals for women in the informal sector.

quoting swami vivekananda, prof akbar husain, dean, faculty of social sciences said, "there is no chance of the welfare of the world unless the condition of women is improved." he pointed out, "women are all powerful if they have strong mind, confidence in their body language and maturity in handling relationships. empowerment is an internal attribute. a woman may feel empowered if she is contended with herself in physical, emotional, mental, social and spiritual terms."

text:
night two.

fear.

i fear womxn.

the emotional abusers in my life were womxn. the ones who psychologically tortured me and gaslighted me as a child were womxn.

it was womxn who got into arguments over me, my health, and took away autonomy.

mostly womxn who set ultimatums upon me. snapped at me. took my things away from me. discarded me. projected onto me.

while mxn have been the sexual abusers in my life. takers. controllers. enforcers. arguing with the womxn about how to handle me. or, in the case of my parents, silently agreeing and allowing the mother to go off in rages. screaming at me.

screaming at me until i had a meltdown or cut.

then the relief of household silence and the pain from my fresh lacerations.

i had an immensely difficult childhood, but on the outside, looking in.. i was well fed after the homeless cycle was broken.
i had lots and lots of toys and video games. clothes. furniture.
i had access to the internet (but was spied on a lot..).
i had education. i went to college. in fact, going to college was how i escaped.

then my parents didn't talk to me much after that. i became even more invisible.

yeah i was loving growing up but i was also tortured and isolated while being subjected to anger, control, and emotional intensity that to this day.. to this very fucking day.. affects how i can socialize and step up in the world.

it sounds ableist outside of this context... but i can't handle people who are intense, angry, or who have frightening mental illness symptoms. i always wind up triggered and feeling like i need to hide.

the paranoia begins.
the fear.
the dreams.
the switching of my alters.
the grief.

i miss my mom. i never really had one. my mother was a shell of her traumas. i remember maybe twice that i saw the part of her that she was protecting from everyone, 27/7.

text:
this picture is about an incident that happened on 23 october.
on 23 october tamil nadu woke up to something that should've stunned it to shame. there is a village called thalavaipatti, there a 13 year old girl named rajalakshmi was beheaded by her neighbour dinesh kumar. she had allegedly spurned his advances. this happened when the #metoo campaigns were going viral, and yet nobody seemed to notice such incident. what happened was, she was sexually harassed by him previously. she even told this to her parents but they couldnt do anything as they were from a dalit family and he was from a dominant caste. that day when chinnaponnu(her mother) abd rajalakshmi were stringing flowers, he came there with sickle and beheaded her inspite of chinnaponnu's intervention. then he headed home with her head where his wife sarada advised him to discard it elsewhere. subsequently they went to police station together and surrendered. sarada convinced the police that he was mentally ill but it was just a plot to save her husband.during the investigation police made it clear that he was mentally and physically sound. the police see this as a caste crime whereas the society sees it as a sex crime. in my opinion its both. now he can come oug on bail, which should not happen. in my opinion the case should be tried under posco act (death penalty). it is such a shame that we all failed to notice such a horrible incident. women have always been worshipped in india and even been the victims of rape, acid attacks and everything. all these put us in shame. something has to be done and put an end to this cruelty . imaginge the state of the parents who lost theif daughter. i want all of us to join our hands together and we might be able stop all this in future. we need justice for rajalakshmi

harrassment of any form is wrong. be it physical or emotional. the idea of sex & consent are mutually exclusive. there canâ€™t be sex without consent. because sex without consent, is not sexâ€”itâ€™s rape, and rapes happen not only in work places , even in relationships and marriages.

we all know that the #metoo movement speaks of the widespread prevalence of sexual assault and harassment, especially in the workplace. it's been a revelation in our society, where many fearless women and few men who've been affected directly, have opened up in public, to stop the entitlement that comes with power of position, the wrongdoer holds, and the deragatory conduct & demeanor the victim gets subjected to.to keep the workplace, a purely professional place of choice. 
whether you're speaking out as part of the #metoo movement or holding on to your story, every single person deserves to feel safe, be happy and live past the physical/mental trauma they've been part of.

easier said that done, living in a society which keeps reminding us of the past we want to forget. however by making a conscious effort, we can get back to living the life we deserve, happy, rejoiceful, one that feels good from the inside. but for that, we need to heal. we need to understand that the past doesn't defile our honour nor define who we are, and what matters is how we want to live in the present leading upto the future.

what better way to heal than talk to someone who truly understands and is qualified to help without passing judgements. :) whoever you're, if you have a story to share and heal from, use my code "metoosurya" to avail a free counseling session with an expert on beamitlive from the smile again foundation. ğŸ˜Š

we are here, we are listening. spread the word and know that you're not alone!

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
there is nothing more beautiful than watching someone concentrate on creating something, unmindful of what goes on around them. and as we all already know, most women, especially those in rural areas, do not sit idle for even a single minute. 
i watched fascinated as this village woman industriously wove dried reed into a basket. with due respect, i omitted capturing her face, as even though i had asked for her consent to click the picture, she had no idea of the geographical extent to which this picture could be viewed, and it would mean my exploiting her lack of this knowledge.....with the current #metoo campaign, it is a welcome time to revisit our meaning of #consent
to me it means a shared similar understanding of what is about to occur or is occurring. if one party thinks differently, then that is not consent....

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the companyâ€™s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when youâ€™re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a personâ€™s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the â€œtraining setâ€ refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your â€œfeature setâ€: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, itâ€™s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data â€“ the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that youâ€™re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

text:
mother me too
40 x 50 cm

everyone knows what mother nature represents. sheâ€™s every plant, vine, and flower, every living animal, big and small, every rock, mountain, ocean, and creek. sheâ€™s everything the earth has ever given us. yet every day we as a species gradually destroy her. the business model based on monetary gain has ruined our connection with nature. so we dump our waste in the oceans, we fill our skies with smog and toxins, we slaughter animals in unimaginable numbers, we destroy acres of precious rainforests, and all of this for corporate profit.

text:
one of the best decisions i ever made was to stop â€˜doingâ€™ family christmases. it was not a healthy environment, i found it deeply stressful to visit my parents house & engage in a charade, a pretense of â€˜familyâ€™, and so the last christmas i spent in my family home was at age 19, over 30 years ago.
.
just because most people are doing something doesnâ€™t mean itâ€™s healthy, right or good for you.
.
make plans now for the holiday or festive season that feel the best, the most fun & relaxing to & for you. if thatâ€™s not spending it with â€˜familyâ€™ consider making plans that will be extra supportive, consider putting things in place in case it feels challenging or difficult - for those without family, or without good family relationships, christmas & other holidays can be a difficult time - if itâ€™s difficult for you put a strategy in place now to support your mental health then.
.

text:
today in class we had a deep dive conversation about domestic violence and i realized that a lot people donâ€™t understand it. someone said, â€œwhy canâ€™t the person just say no or just leave?â€ if you canâ€™t understand that then i certainly hope you never do. â€œi hate bulliesâ€ i wish you understood it so much more than that. itâ€™s not bullying itâ€™s about making who you are not exist anymore and becoming the object of the person hurting you through manipulation, mental abuse, sometimes physical violence and destroy your life, controlling everything using fear. â€œshe canâ€™t be a victim of domestic because there was no physical violenceâ€ this is so not true at all because to be honest, bones heal, bruises disappear, cuts close but mental wounds donâ€™t close, heal or disappear. the abuse becomes a illness like cancer. it can go into remission, but unless you nurture it or work with it, it comes back and breaks you. it hurts you, it makes you sick, it makes afraid again, it makes cry and wanna give up (donâ€™t). your mind becomes a castle that is filled with water of memories and your chained to the floor. all you can do is keep swimming and stay at the top for air. eventually your muscles get stronger and it becomes easier to stay up but if you give up one day you start to drown. itâ€™s not as easy as leave, donâ€™t think about, donâ€™t let them bully you, donâ€™t talk to them anymore, itâ€™s not that easy. 
but, to anyone in this situation reading this if you understand what itâ€™s like to be in that castle then i beg you please, talk to a crisis counselor (203) 853-0418 (milford), call safe futures (860) 447-0366, call sexual assault crisis center (860) 442-0604. do not let someone do this to you or family (yes, even itâ€™s just happening to you your children are watching and they are seeing your pain which is hurting them too.) please donâ€™t give up your too important and you have a story being told. i love you. -moon â€œcastle in your mindâ€ #metoo #connecticut #domesticviolence #domesticviolenceawareness
